{"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"languages":["swift"],"tokens":[{"text":"func","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"enumerated","kind":"identifier"},{"text":"() -> ","kind":"text"},{"text":"EnumeratedSequence","kind":"typeIdentifier","identifier":"doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/EnumeratedSequence","preciseIdentifier":"s:s18EnumeratedSequenceV"},{"text":"<","kind":"text"},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","text":"Self"},{"kind":"text","text":">"}]}]},{"content":[{"level":2,"text":"Return Value","anchor":"return-value","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A sequence of pairs enumerating the sequence."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"kind":"content"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"discussion","text":"Discussion","level":2,"type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This example enumerates the characters of the string “Swift” and prints"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"each character along with its place in the string."}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["for (n, c) in \"Swift\".enumerated() {","    print(\"\\(n): '\\(c)'\")","}","// Prints \"0: 'S'\"","// Prints \"1: 'w'\"","// Prints \"2: 'i'\"","// Prints \"3: 'f'\"","// Prints \"4: 't'\""],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"When you enumerate a collection, the integer part of each pair is a counter"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"for the enumeration, but is not necessarily the index of the paired value.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"These counters can be used as indices only in instances of zero-based,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"integer-indexed collections, such as "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"code":"ContiguousArray","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". For"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"other collections the counters may be out of range or of the wrong type","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to use as an index. To iterate over the elements of a collection with its","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"indices, use the ","type":"text"},{"code":"zip(_:_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" function."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This example iterates over the indices and elements of a set, building a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"list consisting of indices of names with five or fewer letters.","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let names: Set = [\"Sofia\", \"Camilla\", \"Martina\", \"Mateo\", \"Nicolás\"]","var shorterIndices: [Set<String>.Index] = []","for (i, name) in zip(names.indices, names) {","    if name.count <= 5 {","        shorterIndices.append(i)","    }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now that the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"shorterIndices"},{"text":" array holds the indices of the shorter","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"names in the "},{"code":"names","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" set, you can use those indices to access elements in"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"the set."}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["for i in shorterIndices {","    print(names[i])","}","// Prints \"Sofia\"","// Prints \"Mateo\""]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"O(1)","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Complexity"}]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["/documentation/swift/enumeratedsequence/enumerated()"]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift","doc://com.apple.Swift/documentation/Swift/EnumeratedSequence"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Returns a sequence of pairs ("},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"n","type":"text"